# 11. Interview Explanation (30–60 sec)

> We first observe that the answer cannot exceed the array length `n`, so any value greater than `n` can be treated as `n`. Instead of sorting, we count the frequency of each value from `1` to `n`. Then we greedily build the longest valid sequence starting from `1`. The variable `prev` stores the largest value built so far. At each value `num`, the `count[num]` copies can extend the sequence, but they can never create values larger than `num`. Therefore we update `prev = min(prev + count[num], num)`. This gives an `O(n)` time and `O(n)` space solution.

---

# 12. Key Takeaways

* Rearrangement removes order constraints.
* Only decreasing is allowed.
* Maximum answer is never greater than `n`.
* Counting sort avoids `O(n log n)` sorting.
* Greedy always builds the largest possible next value.
* `prev` stores the largest value constructed so far.

